http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: The Personal Finance Model Curriculum is based on the Pennsylvania Academic Standards for Economics, Family and Consumer Science, Career Education and Work, and Pennsylvania Academic Standards in Business, Computer and Information Technology.
Money management includes setting goals and developing a plan for how to spend, save, and share financial resources.
Identify strategies for personal financial management.
Discuss the importance of developing short, medium-, and long-term personal financial goals.
Classify financial goals as short and long term and develop plans to reach goals.
Identify goals and determine steps to achieve them.
Analyze types of consumer behavior and characteristics including but not limited to spending habits, emotional buying, rational buying, and buying power.
Explain how people apply decision-making skills to make financial decisions.
Analyze how unlimited wants and limited resources affect decision-making.
Differentiate between needs and wants and choices people make.
Demonstrate the relationship of the components of a simple spending plan and how that relationship allows for managing income, expenses and savings.
Discuss earning, spending, and saving for financial stability.
Describe the ability to meet basic human needs through different types of purchases.
Identify goods and services people buy and how people use money to make purchases.
Evaluate the impact of internal and external influences on purchasing decisions.
Compare various payment options for purchases.
Identify types of advertising designed to influence personal choice.
Define price and how prices vary for products.
Evaluate how charitable organizations use contributions.
Compare the missions of charitable organizations.
Identify charitable organizations and the services they provide.
Describe ways children can share with others.
Earning capabilities over a lifetime are maximized by career planning, education, and job choices.
Analyze a career goal and develop a plan and timetable for achieving it.
Investigate and present the educational/training requirements, lifetime income potential, and primary duties of at least two jobs of interest.
Describe the risks, costs, and rewards of starting a business.
Explain the difference between a career and a job and why people work.
Differentiate between work and play and identify jobs in the community.
Hypothesize the future income needed to maintain a desired standard of living.
Describe various sources of personal income, including wages, gifts, rent, interest, commissions, tips, etc.
Explain the differences in earning by those in different jobs and with different skills and education.
Identify ways children and adults acquire money.
Analyze and calculate net pay.
Explain the purposes of tax-related forms and complete samples.
Describe taxes and deductions subtracted from gross pay.
Give an example of how governments use taxes we pay.
Explain why the price of an item can be different from the actual amount paid.
Borrowing money has costs and benefits.
Analyze the impact of a positive or negative credit history.
Explain the components of a credit report.
Identify factors that impact a person's ability to borrow money.
Explain what makes someone a good borrower.
Analyze the total cost of a major purchase loan agreement using fixed and variable interest rates, calculated over time.
Develop a logical argument for using a specific credit product to make a purchase.
Explain the difference between simple and compound interest.
Discuss problems associated with not having enough cash and the costs and benefits of borrowing.
Investigate major consumer credit laws and their impact on individuals in debt.
Compare the rights and responsibilities of borrowers and lenders.
Explain the responsibilities of borrowing.
Financial institutions offer services for people to secure, access, and transfer their money.
Analyze the functions of the Federal Reserve and other financial institutions.
Compare advantages and disadvantages of different relating to saving, investing, and borrowing.
Describe financial institutions in the community.
Analyze and complete a financial application.
Compare financial services considering costs and benefits of each.
Explain the differences between a checking and savings account.
Identify places children and adults put their money to keep it safe.
Assess the impact of identity theft.
Examine steps to minimize exposure to identity theft.
Discuss potential consequences of disclosing personal information.
Identify information that is personal and ways to keep it secure.
Risk management strategies are used to protect against potential loss.
Compare how people manage risk through avoidance,reduction, retention, and transfer.
Explain how and why people make end-of-life plans.
Compare common types of risk and basic risk management methods.
Summarize risks that individuals and households face.
Using an age-appropriate activity such as riding a bicycle, predict risks and give examples of how to reduce.
Compare and contrast various suppliers of insurance products and develop criteria to evaluate individual insurance needs.
Describe types of insurance including health, disability, auto, homeowners, renters, life, and long-term care.
Develop a logical argument for having various types of insurance.
Discuss methods to protect valuable items against damage or loss.
Discuss how valuable items might be damaged or lost and ways to protect them.
Saving and investing habits influence lifelong opportunities for financial independence.
Analyze savings goals and options people have at various life stages.
Compare and contrast the various financial tools available to savers.
Identify the costs and benefits of saving.
Define saving and explain why people save.
Evaluate benefits and costs of changes in interest rates for individuals and society.
Compare simple and compound interest.
Explain interest charged versus interest earned.
Develop a definition of wealth considering personal values, priorities, and goals.
Estimate the extent to which assets may increase or decrease in value and describe how people accumulate assets.
Describe how people accumulate tangible and intangible assets.
Critique investment plans in terms of their ability to achieve goals of liquidity, income, growth, and tax benefit.
Analyze the risks and returns of various investments.
Evaluate the benefits of a diversified! investment portfolio.
Discuss the purpose and function of investments.
Analyze the role of federal and state regulators in protecting savers and investors.
